			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I like these suggestions.  I took a break for a week or two to relax, and check out DAoC.  First clue there may be a problem is that you take a break from a game to relax or calm down... <br>  <br> I like DAoC because there's a reason for trade skills.  There's no real incentive, from what I can see, to work on blacksmithing.  I can make banded, but I can't sell it regularly enough to matter.   <br>  <br> There's also less risk in dieing.  Trust me, dieing still sucks.  Knowing that you basically lost some play time is bad enough.  I've stood in GFay trying to get a SoW or invis so I can get safely back to MM to get my corpse.  I've made that run naked and unbuffed a few times.  And I've gotten killed by brownie scouts that seem to have wandered too far away or dark elves that got trained far away from their regular camp a few times.   <br>  <br> I don't have a problem with people selling items for whatever they want to.  But it's discouraging to see that stuff is selling for multiple thousands of pp when I know I've got like 20 to my name (smithing gets expensive when it takes a while to sell the armor). <br>  <br> The quest log would be great.  Seems odd that I'm playing a game on a computer and have to hand-write notes to remember who's supposed to get what. <br>  <br> Downtime is a hassle, especially when you have a rough time getting into a group.  Or when you miss some time with your regular group and they've gained a few levels. <br>  <br> While we're on the topic of groups, I can identify with having a character you enjoy playing that has a rough time getting into a group.  I play a warrior as my main, and have a hard time getting into a group with him.  Also have a wizard that spent two playing sessions trying to get into a group in HH.  I finally just abandoned the idea, and went elsewhere.  Still looking for a non-Oasis group... <br>  <br> Guess that's enough ranting for now... <br> 		

